  "topic_name": "Atomic Structure and Chemical Bonding",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "According to Bohr's model, electrons revolve around the nucleus in fixed orbits (K, L, M, N shells) with definite energy. Maximum electrons per shell is 2n2. Atoms achieve stability by attaining noble gas configuration (8 electrons in outer shell - octet rule, or 2 for hydrogen/helium - duplet rule). Ionic bonding involves transfer of electrons from metal to non-metal, forming oppositely charged ions attracted by electrostatic force. Covalent bonding involves sharing of electrons between non-metal atoms. Electrovalency is the number of electrons transferred; covalency is the number of electrons shared.",
    "rules": [
      "Maximum electrons in shell: 2n2 (K=2, L=8, M=18, N=32)",
      "Valence electrons determine chemical properties",
      "Octet rule: atoms tend to have 8 electrons in outer shell",
      "Duplet rule: hydrogen and helium tend to have 2 electrons",
      "Ionic bond: electron transfer, metal + non-metal",
      "Covalent bond: electron sharing, non-metal + non-metal",
      "Ionic compounds: high melting point, conduct when dissolved/molten",
      "Covalent compounds: low melting point, usually don't conduct"
    ]
  },
